07724nam a22010575i 9781614514053DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20152015gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979631653  a97816145140537 a10.1515/97816145140532doi  a(DE-B1597)212701  a(OCoLC)909907885  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aBIO0180002bisacsh00aMultiple Secularities Beyond the West :bReligion and Modernity in the Global Age /ced. by Marian Burchardt, Matthias Middell, Monika Wohlrab-Sahr. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (317 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReligion and Its Others : Studies in Religion, Nonreligion and Secularity ,x2330-6262 ;v100tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tMultiple Secularities beyond the West: An Introduction -- tPart I: Religious Communities and the State: Fault-Lines of Religion and Secularity in South Asia -- tSecular Anxieties and Transnational Engagements in India -- t“Speaking” the Nation Secular: (E)merging Faces of India -- tAnti-caste Radicalism, Dalit Movements and the Many Critiques of Secular Nationalism in India -- tPart II: Nationalism, Islam and Democratization: Secular Dynamics in the Arab World -- tDeviance as a Phenomenon of Secularity: Islam and Deviants in Twentieth-century Egypt—A Search for Sociological Explanations -- tSecularity Contested: Religion, Identity and the Public Order in the Arab Middle East -- tPart III: Secularities in East Asia -- tJapanese Responses to Imperialist Secularization: The Postwar Movement to Restore Shinto in the Public Sphere -- tThe Religious-Secular Divide at the Community Level in Contemporary Japan -- tPart IV: African Scenarios: (Post‐)Colonial Secularity vs. African Religiosity? -- tMoments of Insurgency: Christianity in South African Politics, from the 18th Century to Today -- tAfter Pentecostalism? Exploring Intellectualism, Secularization and Guiding Sentiments in Africa -- tPart V: The Sacred Secular: Secularities in post-Communist Central and Eastern Europe -- tVulnerable Post-Soviet Secularities: Patterns and Dynamics in Russia and Beyond -- tSocialist Secularities: The Diversity of a Universalist Model -- tConclusions -- tBetween World Society and Multiple Modernities: Comparing Cultural Constructions of Secularity and Institutional Varieties of Secularism -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aQuestions of secularity and modernity have become globalized, but most studies still focus on the West. This volume breaks new ground by comparatively exploring developments in five areas of the world, some of which were hitherto situated at the margins of international scholarly discussions: Africa, the Arab World, East Asia, South Asia, and Central and Eastern Europe.In theoretical terms, the book examines three key dimensions of modern secularity: historical pathways, cultural meanings, and global entanglements of secular formations. The contributions show how differences in these dimensions are linked to specific histories of religious and ethnic diversity, processes of state-formation and nation-building. They also reveal how secularities are critically shaped through civilizational encounters, processes of globalization, colonial conquest, and missionary movements, and how entanglements between different territorially grounded notions of secularity or between local cultures and transnational secular arenas unfold over time.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aGlobalisierung. 4aModernität. 4aReligion. 4aSekularismus. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Religious.2bisacsh  aReligion.  aglobalization.  amodernity.  asecul